{{italic title}}
'''''Epistulae ad Quintum Fratrem''''' ('''''Letters to brother Quintus''''') is a collection of letters from [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] politician and orator [[Cicero|Marcus Tullius Cicero]] to his younger brother [[Quintus Tullius Cicero|Quintus]]. The letters in this collection, when combined with Cicero's other letters, are considered the most reliable sources of information for the period leading up to the fall of the [[Roman Republic]]. His letters to Quintus share a similar quality to those sent to his close friend [[Titus Pomponius Atticus]], written with a freedom and frankness not to be found in his correspondence with others. Traditionally spanning 3 books, and featuring letters from 60 or 59 to 54&nbsp;BCE, this collection may have been first published by Cicero's [[freedman]] and personal secretary [[Marcus Tullius Tiro]] sometime after the deaths of both brothers in 43&nbsp;BCE.<ref>{{Cite book |editor-last=Shackleton Bailey |editor-first=D. R. |editor-link=D. R. Shackleton Bailey |date=May 2002 |title=Letters to Quintus and Brutus. Letter Fragments. Letter to Octavian. Invectives. Handbook of Electioneering |url=http://www.loebclassics.com/view/LCL462/2002/volume.xml |publisher=Harvard University Press |access-date=5 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Cicero}}</ref>

==References==
{{Reflist}}

